My wife is the pokemon collector in our family (I’m more into MtG), so over the last week whenever I’m gacha-machining and pull anything halfway decent or that I think she might like (read: cute) I call her over and she’s got final say in what is kept for the collection vs sold back

There’s a bunch that from a purely $$$ perspective seem like not-great holds to me, but the heart want what the heart wants so our collection continues to grow

It’s one of the key differences between NFTs and Pokemon cards. With NFTs, the vast majority were crypto degens trying to make money and the artists and true collectors made up the tiny minority

With Pokemon cards, there are sooooooo many genuine fans and collectors and while yes, a lot of people have been getting into it lately purely for the $$$, the ratio still seems heavily skewed towards collectors just wanting to collect

Both, we’re ripping physical packs and I’m also slowly starting to collect digitally

The connection is companies like @Collector_Crypt and @Beezie have been tokenising RWAs, largely Pokemon cards that are graded and secured in vaults

So you can own the cards and trade them without having to deal with shipping (and customs) and take physical custody of them - huge for people like me in Australia 

But if you ever do want to redeem the physicals, you can do that too

Very cool use case for blockchain tech imo

